sentence: Am I doing enough
reframing1: I care about my dad a lot and and I want to do what's best for him. I might not be perfect all the time, but I know I'm doing the best I can.
reframing2: When I worry whether or not I'm doing enough, I am going to ask my dad to help me make a list of what he regularly needs during the day and things I can do that would make him feel comfortable.

sentence: I've been practicing but I'm not making any progress
reframing1: I feel self conscious that my teacher is pointing out places to improve but that is this person's job!
reframing2: I'm glad my teacher is helping me find ways to improve.

sentence: We won't be able to find the store before it closes.
reframing1: I am feeling anxious and overwhelmed. Let me take a moment to refocus so we can work together to find the right way to go to get to the store on time.
reframing2: It is possible the store may close but being lost is not purposeful. If the store closes before we can get there we can just figure out another option to get what we need to get through the night.

sentence: I felt like a failure and am ashamed I made this mistake
reframing1: Everyone makes mistakes. This is something I can fix.
reframing2: It makes sense I am ashamed about this mistake. I will fix it.

sentence: My grades are important and I did poorly
reframing1: This is just one test that contributes to my overall grade.
reframing2: I will calm down before the next test.

sentence: ill never be able to find a good job
reframing1: There are many reasons why I may not have gotten this job and this experience does not dictate my future
reframing2: This job may not have worked out but I got interview practice for my next one.

sentence: Fuck you
reframing1: It's okay to feel angry. I can focus on what I can control and let go of what I can't
reframing2: Sometimes I feel so angry, I don't know how to express myself. It might help to write down what I'm feeling and think about what's behind my anger

sentence: I made a deadline and missed it.
reframing1: how can i make it up to my friend?
reframing2: it's disappointing when i miss deadlines. it has been a busy week. i am going to prioritize the project now.

sentence: This is going to cause us to break up.
reframing1: I'm anxious that my partner's relocation could damage our relationship.
reframing2: My girlfriend cares about me and we will figure this out together

sentence: He is avoiding me
reframing1: I only asked him a week ago and I know he has a lot going on. I should check back in with him next week to see if he has the time to help me out right now.
reframing2: My friend may be busy right now. I should try to ask another friend.

sentence: What if I never see her again?
reframing1: I'm feeling sad and lonely that my love has left. I hope we can reunite in the future or that I have the chance to fall in love again.
reframing2: It hurts to watch my love leave. I wonder what the future holds for me romantically but I will remember the positive parts of this relationship fondly.

sentence: Am I insane?
reframing1: It's ok to feel self-conscious and feel frustrated when I can't figure something, but I may need to get help for the self-harming because that doesn't seem healthy.
reframing2: These behaviors don't make me insane, but they're still concerning and I should probably reach out for help

sentence: I worry too much
reframing1: Even though I am running late, I can still focus while driving Better getting there safely than not at all
reframing2: My anxiety and worry issues are a problem I am having problems with staying focused while driving

sentence: Suicidal thoughts
reframing1: Even very attractive people sometimes have a hard time finding love. Dating is hard, and I don't need to beat myself up.
reframing2: I may not always like the way I look, but I can still find someone who thinks I'm beautiful.

sentence: I did something wrong
reframing1: I'm feeling sad, anxious, and lonely as my partner leaves. I'm thankful for the positive parts of our relationship and will mourn this loss, but I know I will eventually find the person who is right for me.
reframing2: I'm feeling hurt that my partner left and I need to process how we got to this point.

sentence: My partner will leave me if my depression doesn't go away soon.
reframing1: Did boyfriend 6 yrs ago leave due to the  your depression too?
reframing2: He needs to be more support of you with your depression

sentence: I failed our company & myself
reframing1: Did I? I am merely a small part of this company and shouldn't take the sole responsibility for its successes and failures
reframing2: I'm a small part of this company and shouldn't take the sole responsibility for its successes and failures

sentence: he didn't respect our initial commitment
reframing1: it makes sense that i was aggravated because of the changes. it doesnt mean he doesnt respect our initial commitment. something might have come up
reframing2: my boyfriend respects our commitment. something probably came up

sentence: I feel like a bad wife and mom
reframing1: I am doing my best given my current circumstances. That does not mean I'm a bad wife or mom.
reframing2: I am going through a difficult time right now. It is ok that I am not doing as much for the family as much as I'd like to.

sentence: I would not find a job
reframing1: I feel anxious about my work performance. I know that if I improve and try my hardest I will find something I am good at and have success.
reframing2: There are things I could have done better to keep that job. I will work to grow and try to do better next time.

sentence: They hate me.
reframing1: What I do affects the group
reframing2: I need to be more aware of my groups needs

sentence: The kids will never settle down.
reframing1: I overreacted by yelling. Kids will be kids and they will settle down eventually.
reframing2: It is normal for kids to be fidgety at bedtime. There will be nights where they settle down easily and nights where they don't settle down easily like tonight.

sentence: I'm self-centered
reframing1: I may be "self-centered" but I did the right thing
reframing2: Just because I refused to help a friend, doesn't mean I'm "self-centered"

sentence: I must not have been doing a good job
reframing1: My boss may be angry about something else, I know I have been doing a good job.
reframing2: My boss is in a bad mood, that doesn't mean I am responsible.

sentence: I'm not good enough for her.
reframing1: I feel sad that she turned me down but maybe this is for the best.
reframing2: Getting rejected hurts. There are many reasons she could have said no. I'll recover and eventually find the person who is right for me.

sentence: They will never want to go out with me
reframing1: I'm sure their response was not about me, this coworker must have other things going on.
reframing2: The coworker must be busy, maybe they will accept my invitation next time.

sentence: She didn't like me anymore.
reframing1: If my girlfriend doesn't like me anymore, I trust that she will tell me that and not just ignore me. Guessing at what others are thinking is not fair to either one of us.
reframing2: My girlfriend has not responded, but I should be patient and not jump to conclusions about what this means until I talk to her

sentence: i cant trust people
reframing1: Although I am scared and I feel that I can't trust people right now, there are things I can do to change that.  I can go to therapy and I can practice learning to trust people in a safe environment.
reframing2: To say I can't trust people is trying to predict the future.  I am focusing only on my fear and ignoring the facts.  It is possible that there are many people I can trust.  I can definitely improve the odds by seeing a counselor to help me deal with my fears.

sentence: I'm worthless
reframing1: I am not worthless.
reframing2: I may have shortcomings in my personal life but my professional life is thriving and I am well thought of at work.  Therefore, I am not completely worthless.

sentence: I'm a failure
reframing1: I now have time to get caught up on household tasks I did not have time to do while working.  I also have time to devote to my arts and crafts which really helps to boost my self-esteem.
reframing2: I am not a failure.  Many people are out of work.  My worth is not based on my employment.

sentence: She needs to stop discussing this.
reframing1: I was embarrassed and I should give my boss feedback that I was feeling defensive. Hopefully we can resolve this in the future.
reframing2: My supervisor was being unfair to me by discussing this in front of people and I was hurt. I should talk to her in private about this and how I would like to receive feedback in the future.

sentence: I'm never going to be useful to society and it isn't worth living in because humans are extremely hard to understand
reframing1: I feel I will never accomplish anything in life  so I give up or maybe 🤔 a trauma counselor can help me get thru this
reframing2: I give up on life because I am having difficulty with flashbacks of highschool

sentence: it's all my fault
reframing1: Though I messed up, I've learned a lot from myself and can improve this behavior.
reframing2: I messed things up. I have some things I need to work on if I want to be in a relationship again.

sentence: I feel unloved and unwanted by my mother and siblings
reframing1: My family may not know about the tornadoes. I am sure if they did, they would reach out because I know they care about me. Just because they don't check in this one time, does not mean I am not loved by them.
reframing2: It is possible nobody in my extended family heard about the tornadoes. I am sure if they did, they would reach out.

sentence: I'm incompetent
reframing1: I may be "incompetent", but atleast I attempted the task
reframing2: I'm not "incompetent" as a whole. There are certain skills I possess

sentence: He does not appreciate anything I do for him.
reframing1: I can't anticipate all of my son's needs, and he needs to ask for help when he needs it.
reframing2: I can't assume what my son needs or wants. I want to ask him how I can be supportive of his needs.

sentence: I am responsible for her mistakes.
reframing1: My sister's mistake is not my responsibility.
reframing2: My sister made a mistake, but that doesn't mean I should be blamed.

sentence: Why did I overact like this
reframing1: I was upset by this action and that is okay
reframing2: I was upset by this and may have reacted rather than responded. I can learn from this for next time

sentence: I’ll never be able to hold a job.
reframing1: My mental illnesses make some things harder for me, but I will be able to find a job that is a good fit for me.
reframing2: I'm going through a hard time right now, but that does not mean I won't be able to hold a job eventually.

sentence: No one cares about me
reframing1: My partner doesn't care about me and broke up with me, but many other people care about me.
reframing2: My partner and I are not together anymore but that does not mean he doesn't still care about me in some way.  I will have other relationships with people who do care deeply about me but it may not happen right away.

sentence: He's so damn inconsiderate
reframing1: My roommate may not have known that I needed to use the bathroom at the time. He probably would have given me the time to use the bathroom if I had known I needed to use it. Next time this happens, I should be transparent about my schedule.
reframing2: My roommate was probably upset like I was. Maybe I was the one not being considerate in the moment. I should apologize to him.

sentence: I feel like people out there try to take advantage of me and also betray me .
reframing1: I don't know why they pushed me. Maybe it had nothing to do with me.
reframing2: One person mistreated me, but there are other people who care about me.

sentence: I shouldn't have posted it
reframing1: I am proud to have posted my work
reframing2: I can still be proud of my work. It is totally up to me whether I should post it or not

sentence: Why can't they cooperate on this?
reframing1: It sounds like there is no way to create a perfect plan for this party, I will continue to try my best to be a good leader.
reframing2: My plan is not meeting the needs of everyone involved, I should try collaborating with others or get their input on what plan would be best for everyone.

sentence: The thought that he does not care about me anymore.
reframing1: My husband canceling our plans doesn't necessarily mean he doesn't care about me anymore. We have a lot going on right now. I need to talk with him about how we can find ways to spend more time together.
reframing2: I am disappointed he canceled our plans but I should talk with him to understand why he canceled and what alternative plans we may be able to make together.
